/NATIONALITY> family whose second environment, the <GEOGHERITAGE>northern wilderness</GEOGHERITAGE>, became deeply familiar to her from long summers in the bush where her father did his research.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Her mother was born <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret Killam" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:77839530-785e-4011-a324-eb315367a85e">Margaret Killam</NAME>, a member of a Nova Scotia family which acquired prominence as merchants, politicians, financiers, and latterly philanthropists.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="FATHER"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Her father, Dr <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Carl Edmund" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:703e9a23-f9b9-41f0-8acc-093bbd1343b6">Carl Edmund Atwood</NAME>, was an <JOB>academic</JOB> <JOB REG="scientist">entomologist</JOB>.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> spent her childhood in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Ottawa</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Sault Ste Marie</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, with summers in the bush area north of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Temiscaming</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Quebec"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Quiet 22" DBREF="33945" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d2f9da2f-018b-4d40-8a5e-eca7ffaa1091">22</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Education</HEADING><EDUCATION MODE="DOMESTIC"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Margaret's earliest education was at home—from her mother, and from the major educational experience offered by her wilderness summers. She later enumerated the pop-cultural forms of her childhood as the movies, radio, the funny papers and comic books.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 31" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">31</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION><EDUCATION MODE="INSTITUTIONAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She attended elementary school, and then from <DATE VALUE="1952-09" CERTAINTY="AFTER">1952</DATE> <SCHOOL INSTITUTION="DAYSCHOOL" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="SECONDARY" REG="Leaside High School,, Toronto" RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES"><ORGNAME REG="Leaside High School,, Toronto" STANDARD="Leaside High School,, Toronto" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:74a08934-d27f-4e02-8b41-f696ec5cbb4f">Leaside High School</ORGNAME></SCHOOL> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, both in the Protestant public school system operating in Ontario alongside a Catholic one. She and her schoolmates got prayers and <TEXT><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REND="normal">Bible</TITLE></TEXT> readings every day, memorized psalms and other biblical passages, and took the occasional <SUBJECT>Religious Knowledge</SUBJECT> course. The <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><SUBJECT>English Literature</SUBJECT> curriculum was resolutely British</QUOTE>: <TEXT><NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cf31f8e7-ff5a-463a-adb8-20d1e1c5d8a3">Shakespeare</NAME></TEXT>, <TEXT>English Romantic and Victorian poets</TEXT>, and novels by <TEXT><NAME STANDARD="Eliot, George" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:dca30947-feee-44db-820e-bbcc21038396">George Eliot</NAME></TEXT> and <TEXT><NAME STANDARD="Hardy, Thomas" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:77c44657-07fa-42b2-849a-948a74185ed5">Thomas Hardy</NAME></TEXT>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 9" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>From <DATE VALUE="1957-08" CERTAINTY="AFTER">1957</DATE> she attended <SCHOOL RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY" REG="Victoria College,, Toronto"><ORGNAME REG="Victoria College,, University of Toronto" STANDARD="Victoria College,, University of Toronto" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23502bb9-86bd-44a8-b481-ecd3c1ddcd35">Victoria College</ORGNAME></SCHOOL>, <SCHOOL INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY" REG="University of Toronto"><ORGNAME REG="University of Toronto" STANDARD="University of Toronto" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ab1b87c1-10a5-404f-bb05-01e3d5af9ee9">University of Toronto</ORGNAME></SCHOOL>. Canadian publishing and the arts in Canada, broadly considered, had not yet recovered from the second world war. There were no cheap reprints of new Canadian books, and authors like <NAME STANDARD="Laurence, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:f60cb2c0-2cb3-4dec-888e-603388677a9e">Margaret Laurence</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Gallant, Mavis" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:5a6c285e-41e1-4265-a1e7-4e79905e034a">Mavis Gallant</NAME>, and <NAME STANDARD="Richler, Mordecai" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:8a4b9e11-3b7b-4a2e-b5be-937c56ae46f3">Mordecai Richler</NAME> were living abroad.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 33" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">33</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> At university <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> first became aware of <SUBJECT>Canadian literature</SUBJECT> as a subject of study and a source of pleasure, a discovery which she felt she owed to two of her teachers in particular, <INSTRUCTOR><NAME STANDARD="Frye, Northrop" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:f0f8ca9b-ce3a-4fd3-818c-4ef8f12ac14f">Northrop Frye</NAME></INSTRUCTOR> and <INSTRUCTOR><NAME STANDARD="Macpherson, Jay" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:26d331ea-3600-4f67-af8f-1e3fcc1d56e1">Jay Macpherson</NAME></INSTRUCTOR>. For her <DEGREE>BA in English</DEGREE> (awarded in <DATE VALUE="1961-06" CERTAINTY="C">1961</DATE>) she studied the canon from <TEXT>Anglo-Saxon literature</TEXT> to <TEXT><NAME STANDARD="Eliot, T. S." REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:467d3de9-afa8-4b78-b16d-b647703eeb8e">T. S. Eliot</NAME></TEXT>; in her final year she discovered <TEXT><NAME STANDARD="Watson, Sheila" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:e839087f-9820-4e16-b939-5c7baa456579">Sheila Watson</NAME></TEXT> and <TEXT><NAME STANDARD="Blais, Marie-Claire" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2c886c48-45b9-4580-b542-37093a2a1f79">Marie-Claire Blais</NAME></TEXT>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 36-7" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">36-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She spent the year after her graduation studying <SUBJECT>Victorian literature</SUBJECT> at <SCHOOL INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY" REG="Radcliffe College,, Harvard University"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study at Harvard" REG="Radcliffe College" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:dc62d4ca-c394-4c1f-972e-4c3dcc87f3f2">Radcliffe College</ORGNAME></SCHOOL>, <SCHOOL INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY" REG="Harvard University"><ORGNAME REG="Harvard University" STANDARD="Harvard University" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:fbee61b4-91fd-4817-a70b-5f30e6b461d9">Harvard</ORGNAME></SCHOOL> (then an all-female institution), and then began on doctoral studies at Toronto. She broke off her doctorate in order to work, then resumed it at Harvard in <DATE VALUE="1965-09" CERTAINTY="C">1965</DATE>, where she held a <AWARD>Woodrow Wilson Fellowship</AWARD>. The new subject of her research (not completed) was the English <SUBJECT>gothic novel</SUBJECT>. <BIBCITS/></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Jobs</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P> Back in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE> between periods of study, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> took a job in <DATE VALUE="1963-08" CERTAINTY="C">1963</DATE> with a <JOB>market research</JOB> company, and then taught at the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME REG="University of British Columbia" STANDARD="University of British Columbia" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cc401a42-70e9-4397-82cd-7935b95a115a">University of British Columbia</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>, <DATERANGE CERTAINTY="C" FROM="1964-09" TO="1965-06" EXACT="BOTH">1964-5</DATERANGE>.<BIBCITS/> After this she taught briefly at <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="Sir George Williams University" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:16173d72-2e46-4ae8-b59c-82a18352f74f">Sir George Williams University</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Montreal</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Quebec"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Alberta" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:6a9d995b-4cd6-460f-9c55-7e83669ad6a8">University of Alberta</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Edmonton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Alberta"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, and <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="York University" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3a062274-036e-4bc2-84ef-f34dd4d7ccde">York University</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>. She was <JOB>Writer in Residence</JOB> at the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Toronto" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ab1b87c1-10a5-404f-bb05-01e3d5af9ee9">University of Toronto</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER> in 1972-3, and has since held several other Writer in Residence positions in the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE> and one at <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="Macquarie University" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:bc3ccac1-de9c-45b1-8a2b-8cc4d54e93c2">Macquarie University</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>, <PLACE><GEOG>Australia</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="DLB 251 online" DBREF="18329" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0d09bdb1-b194-4ef5-808d-7b663a244c99">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Personal Life</HEADING><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><MARRIAGE><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1967-06-09">9 June 1967</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> was married in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Boston</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Massachusetts"/><GEOG REG="USA"/></PLACE> to <NAME STANDARD="Polk, James" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:95414d5f-d800-4d31-97e0-a419c5ffbe04">James Polk</NAME>, whom she met while she was a graduate student at <ORGNAME REG="Harvard University" STANDARD="Harvard University" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:fbee61b4-91fd-4817-a70b-5f30e6b461d9">Harvard</ORGNAME>. <SEPARATION>They separated in summer 1972.</SEPARATION></CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="DLB 251 online" DBREF="18329" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0d09bdb1-b194-4ef5-808d-7b663a244c99">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><DIVORCE>Their divorce followed in <DATE VALUE="1977">1977</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="DLB 251 online" DBREF="18329" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0d09bdb1-b194-4ef5-808d-7b663a244c99">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></DIVORCE></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MARRIAGE></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Graeme Gibson</HEADING><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICYES"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><LIVESWITH>In 1972 <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> began a relationship with writer <NAME STANDARD="Gibson, Graeme" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:e4a0c2dc-af59-4db9-b3bc-e01e0db950fd">Graeme Gibson</NAME>, with whom she lived until his death in <DATE VALUE="2019-09-18">September 2019</DATE>.</LIVESWITH></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="DAUGHTER"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><CHILDREN NUMBER="1">They have one daughter, born on <DATE VALUE="1976-05-17">17 May 1976</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="DLB 251 online" DBREF="18329" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0d09bdb1-b194-4ef5-808d-7b663a244c99">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHILDREN></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="VISITED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> has been a lifelong Torontonian, but has lived for periods of time  in widely separated places: <PLACE><REGION>British Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Edmonton"/> <REGION>Alberta</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE> (1968-70), the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Australia</GEOG></PLACE>, and (1970-1) in Europe—<PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"/>, <GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG>Italy</GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Berlin">West Berlin</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Germany" REG="GDR"/></PLACE>.<BIBCITS/></P><P>In winter 1983 Atwood and Gibson spent six months in England. She mentions both a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">cobblestone ex-fisherman's cottage with cold stone floors</QUOTE> and a rectory at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Blakeney</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Norfolk</REGION><GEOG REG="England"/></PLACE>, reputedly haunted by nuns. She was engaged in futile struggle with the complicated time layers of a never-finished historical fiction, finding consolation in the Tudor novels of <NAME STANDARD="Plaidy, Jean" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:69fae8d0-6109-4899-9f92-f206c709df0c">Jean Plaidy</NAME>. She came home to abandon her project and write <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Handmaid's Tale</TITLE>.<BIBCITS/></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Apart from these sojourns, and a six-year period living with Gibson and their small daughter on a farm near <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Alliston</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>Ontario</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> has lived in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Public and Literary Life</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> has spoken at length about the literary life in Toronto in the 1960s and 70s: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">improvisational, inventive, and far from top-heavy with a sense of [its] own importance.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 20" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">20</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> During <DATERANGE FROM="1971" TO="1973" EXACT="BOTH">1971-3</DATERANGE> she was editor of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Anansi Press" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:a8d34c78-3439-4140-aef7-ba1c849a8934">Anansi Press</ORGNAME> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, and she later served on its board.<BIBCITS/> She was also one of the <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES" REG="entertainment organizer">organizers and impresarios</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> of the All-Star Eclectic Typewriter Revue, a <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES" REG="fundraiser">fundraising</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> entertainment for the recently-formed <ORGNAME STANDARD="Writers' Union of Canada" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:461063dc-7fa4-4be6-b48c-5844dadc4117">Writers' Union of Canada</ORGNAME> on 9 May 1974 (or possibly on this day a year or two later) at which writers and reviewers performed, and Atwood herself <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES" REG="dancer">took part in dance routines</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> on snowshoes and in kilts.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 20-5" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">20-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The revue, she says, brought together Canadian authors of all ages and regions, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">working as a team and making idiots of themselves for a common cause.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 30" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">30</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Later, in <DATERANGE FROM="1982" TO="1983" EXACT="BOTH">1982-3</DATERANGE>, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> was President of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Writers' Union of Canada" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:461063dc-7fa4-4be6-b48c-5844dadc4117">Writers' Union of Canada</ORGNAME>. She was President of the Canadian branch of <ORGNAME REG="PEN International" STANDARD="PEN International" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:962e817d-f973-4458-9f80-2826b7f98c49">PEN International</ORGNAME> in 1984-6. She became a Vice-President of Pen International on 11 July 2007, joining other such distinguished writers as <NAME STANDARD="Gordimer, Nadine" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:5094ec46-3f4f-4506-85a7-1ac14895d229">Nadine Gordimer</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Morrison, Toni" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9064f8fd-4c4f-45f7-9c18-d4be2696e925">Toni Morrison</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA online" DBREF="16185" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d0b0dae0-b788-454a-964d-dd2a25ec5dab"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Caitlin Smith" DBREF="46869" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:f32682ec-f6b2-4202-82a2-d55573258200"/></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> has taken an increasingly prominent role in shaping opinion on urgent questions confronting Canadians and others living with the new global economy. In articles, lectures, and interviews she has examined environmental issues, nationalism, governance, peace and war, literacy, and human rights (especially prisoners' rights, especially through <ORGNAME STANDARD="PEN International" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:962e817d-f973-4458-9f80-2826b7f98c49">PEN</ORGNAME>). For PEN's Day of the Imprisoned Writer, <DATE VALUE="2016-11-15">15 November 2016</DATE>, Atwood wrote <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an open message of solidarity</QUOTE> in support of imprisoned Turkish writer <NAME STANDARD="Erdogan, Asli">Asli Erdogan</NAME> (no relation of President <NAME STANDARD="Erdogan, Recep Tayyip">Recep Tayyip Erdogan</NAME>): <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Even through the concrete walls of your prison . . . we can still hear your voice. . . . Although you are in prison, you are not alone.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meghji 6" DBREF="91965" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:af8ca069-fb31-4dd7-85f6-26fbe62e969f">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>She enjoys being at home with pop culture (she has sung with the Canadian indie rock band <ORGNAME STANDARD="The Sadies" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9d8d4e7f-cb0e-48a0-9423-a95470e494ba">The Sadies</ORGNAME>) and is an <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="nerd">innovator (among writers) in the uses of social media, of new hybrid genres, and of the web</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> in general.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><RESEARCHNOTE>Move this DIV1 to end of Life section, for chronological flow.</RESEARCHNOTE><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In 2019 <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> let it be known that she had been a personal friend for ten years of <NAME STANDARD="Dorsey, Jack" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2a76cca2-a990-499a-baf2-055d8ef245c2">Jack Dorsey</NAME>, CEO of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Twitter" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3c0b78f3-2431-4a66-8048-2aefe3909cd6">Twitter</ORGNAME>. Dorsey explained that he was a long-time admirer of her novels, having come to them through her poetry.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Houpt" DBREF="152261" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:5ace0867-fb55-412d-af76-5ea8d29a38ea">Houpt</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In 2012 <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> launched a web space entitled <ORGNAME STANDARD="Fanado" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:f38e70dc-ec44-4aa9-94aa-db9b6e8bf6d2">Fanado</ORGNAME> (http://fanado.com) designed to facilitate online contact between artists and creators of all kinds and their admirers, consumers, or fans, particularly through virtual meet-and-greet sessions and remote signatures. As an example of its work, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> remote-signed a portrait of her painted by <NAME STANDARD="Zhelisko, Oksana" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4ba9b01b-9698-40a5-88a0-1dddfc4f91e7">Oksana Zhelisko</NAME>, an artist in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Edmonton</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>Alberta</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>. The artist, delighted at virtually meeting her model, put the signed portrait up for sale on <ORGNAME STANDARD="eBay" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0eb092d9-ddd1-4884-968f-54593ff58ed1">eBay</ORGNAME> to raise money for Fanado.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Fanado" DBREF="73986" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:1d07069f-df91-4e2f-acd0-f9cf22e99a48"/> <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Today in Literature, 8 September 2015" DBREF="48925" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4b2f1644-acce-494b-ac5b-1c966248dcbc">8 September 2015</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wheeler" DBREF="151283" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ada94f99-4e95-4e5b-882d-00378be24d02"/></BIBCITS> In early summer 2016 <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> attended a major event hosted in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>San Diego</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="California"/><GEOG REG="USA"/></PLACE> by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Comic-Con International" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4cb0a62c-3c6b-4774-971f-47860619048c">Comic-Con International</ORGNAME>, an organization that brings together enthusiasts for old-style comic books and new-style graphic fiction.<BIBCITS/> She took a cameo role (as an oppressive guard) in the televized version of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Handmaid's Tale</TITLE>, 2017.</P><P>MA has been condemned for her part as a signatory of the November 2016 UBC Accountable open letter, which called for due process for an academic at the <ORGNAME REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca//orlando:cc401a42-70e9-4397-82cd-7935b95a115a" STANDARD="University of British Columbia">University of British Columbia</ORGNAME> who in 2016 was accused of sexual assault and fired following the university's investigation of the case, and for her subsequent writing about the #MeToo movement.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood"/></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1></BIOGRAPHY><WRITING><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><DIV1><HEADING>Juvenilia</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Quiet Game, and Other Early Works</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33945" PLACEHOLDER="MA, A Quiet Game, and Other Early Works, 1997" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d2f9da2f-018b-4d40-8a5e-eca7ffaa1091"/><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY>At <DATE VALUE="1945-11-18" CERTAINTY="BY">five</DATE> years old <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> put together a little book of <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA"> <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poems</TGENRE></TGENRE> (some discovered, some composed) entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">Rhyming Cats</TITLE>. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">Also as a child, she says, she wrote a kind of <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA"><TGENRE GENRENAME="SCIENCEFICTION">science fiction</TGENRE></TGENRE> set in outlandish places like the planet Saturn.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Ustopia 25" DBREF="70827" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23f20627-a274-4888-9a84-67b533ed5490">25</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE></PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY> She has allowed some of her <TGENRE GENRENAME="JUVENILIA">childhood and schoolgirl writings</TGENRE> to reach print: two very short stories and a poem in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Quiet Game, and Other Early Works</TITLE>, edited by <NAME STANDARD="Chung, Kathy" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:540df892-2fef-4c7a-97bf-8e97d5811ac4">Kathy Chung</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Grace, Sherrill" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2640412e-d9ec-4321-b41f-fe09fd69e9b8">Sherrill Grace</NAME>, for the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Juvenilia Press" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:120abdba-89c5-4d2a-a5a8-182f02b10609">Juvenilia Press</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Edmonton</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>Alberta</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, in 1997, and the Rhyming Cats verses, a story, and some dramatic pieces with parodies of well-known songs, in a second Juvenila Press volume , 2020. She uses different forms on her typescripts: <SOCALLED>Peggy Atwood</SOCALLED> and <SOCALLED>M. E. Atwood</SOCALLED>.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="VERSIFICATION">The five-year-old <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> was already self-conscious about her work: a couplet about <TTHEMETOPIC>fairies and magic</TTHEMETOPIC>, rhyming on times / chimes, leads on to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">This <SIC>rymes</SIC></QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McMaster vi" DBREF="33946" QTDIN="QTDINYES" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b470e34a-9379-46d6-b1b5-cf32c877116b">vi</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTECHNIQUES> The title story of the first printed volume, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">A Quiet Game</TITLE>, begins slyly, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The little boy was really just a little boy, only cleaner.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Quiet 1" DBREF="33945" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d2f9da2f-018b-4d40-8a5e-eca7ffaa1091">1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TPLOT>The story presents his mother in the kitchen, slicing peaches with deadly efficiency for canning, quite without sympathy for the bored child who is not allowed to play outside because of the mud. There is no sympathy for the mother either, until the shock ending, when the child now banging his head against the bedpost thinks, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I'm playing I'm you, Mother. I'm playing I'm you.</QUOTE></TPLOT> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Quiet 4" DBREF="33945" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d2f9da2f-018b-4d40-8a5e-eca7ffaa1091">4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS"><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">A Recent Grave</TITLE> presents a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>teenage couple</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who like to walk in a cemetery, startled by their encounter with the naked grief of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>bereaved old woman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</TSETTINGPLACE> The girl is moved by emotional connection with somebody so remote, but again Atwood, after moving her reader, closes on a feminist-inspired shock. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Joe and I didn't go back after that. Joe didn't see why.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Quiet 12" DBREF="33945" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d2f9da2f-018b-4d40-8a5e-eca7ffaa1091">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Male indifference, it seems, has closed off the avenue to grief and connection. The poem here, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Pause before Transition</TITLE>, enumerates with gusto the detail of an urban early spring: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Hydrants and garbage cans / Squat darkly on the walks . . . . And old men coughing in the backs of streetcars.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Quiet 7" DBREF="33945" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d2f9da2f-018b-4d40-8a5e-eca7ffaa1091">7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Poetry</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES>In 1960s <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, says Atwood, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poetry</TGENRE> had an importance in the literary landscape that it hasn't had since. Among the young writers I knew, most were poets. <PCIRCULATION>We gathered our poems into collections, of which we didn't expect to sell more than a couple of hundred copies.</PCIRCULATION> . . . The kind of writing we wanted to do was experimental, quirky, non-commercial.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91087" PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Shale 36" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cbe7416a-2881-4a66-867c-ed0d141ce7b9">36</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Early Volumes and Portfolios</HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33948" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Double Persephone, 1961" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d4633025-985d-4ce7-87ae-601cf2c549c6"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="JEB" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1961">1961</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><PMODEOFPUBLICATION PUBLICATIONMODE="SELF-PUBLICATION"><RRECOGNITIONS>In the year she graduated with a BA in English, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> self-published with <ORGNAME STANDARD="Hawkshead Press" REG="Hawkshead Press" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:32cf674e-caec-40dc-ab9a-4dff7751dee5">Hawkshead Press</ORGNAME> of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE> her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poetry</TGENRE> volume, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Double <TCHARACTERNAME>Persephone</TCHARACTERNAME></TITLE> (hand-set and designed by herself), for which she won the <RRECOGNITIONNAME>E. J. Pratt Medal for Poetry</RRECOGNITIONNAME>.</RRECOGNITIONS></PMODEOFPUBLICATION></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="91088" PLACEHOLDER="Carrière ix" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3a2c4501-b51c-43d1-9c11-0fb23b6f1d43">ix</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New Wave Canada" DBREF="33925" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:822aaf87-4086-4ac1-a9d6-437277a12b8a"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:e5b0bfc8-0600-4e93-a0d7-bd3b45d345bb"/></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PAUTHORSHIP><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>The volume (which has a blank white cover and gives the author's name as <SOCALLED>M. E. Atwood</SOCALLED>) launched this press's <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Market Book</TITLE> series.<BIBCITS/></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></PAUTHORSHIP></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE">This work is an early reflection of <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME>'s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">interest in classical and popular <TGENRE GENRENAME="MYTH">mythologies</TGENRE>, especially those concerning women.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMODEOFPUBLICATION PUBLICATIONMODE="LIMITEDEDITION"><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>The <ORGNAME STANDARD="Cranbrook Academy of Art" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:25f6255e-03f9-49b1-b52c-dd97ecdcd797">Cranbrook Academy of Art</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bloomfield Hills</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>Michigan</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"/></PLACE>, began in 1964 to issue <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME>'s portfolios jointly produced with artist <NAME STANDARD="Pachter, Charles" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:7fdbe485-39ff-4c95-aeec-e6cc4d2c8080">Charles Pachter</NAME>. In 1966 it published fifteen copies each of: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Speeches for Doctor Frankenstein</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Expeditions">Expeditions: Poems</TITLE>, signed by the artist and in the case of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Expeditions</TITLE> by the author. These take the form of portfolios rather than books, having title-pages but no binding. The paper is heavy, hand-made, deckle-edged, and the boldly sketched illustrations occasionally surround the text in the manner of <NAME STANDARD="Blake, William" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9c727514-edd1-49dd-a6c3-b553e763e76e">Blake</NAME>.<BIBCITS/></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></PMODEOFPUBLICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE" GENDEROFAUTHOR="WOMAN"><TCHARACTERNAME>Doctor Frankenstein</TCHARACTERNAME> begins as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I, the performer / in the tense arena,</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Frankenstein i" DBREF="34019" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:76627c2f-b08f-40b5-beeb-e4673598483a">i</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> working in a void upon emptiness. He confronts his potential creation like an opponent. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The thing / refuses to be shaped, it moves / like yeast.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Frankenstein iii" DBREF="34019" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:76627c2f-b08f-40b5-beeb-e4673598483a">iii</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The themes of <NAME STANDARD="Shelley, Mary" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:6d158d02-cf73-4f60-b53b-d88c9abf73a8">Mary Shelley</NAME>'s novel are delicately adumbrated without the mention of her name. The creator demands: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Knowing that the work is mine / how can I love you?</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Frankenstein v" DBREF="34019" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:76627c2f-b08f-40b5-beeb-e4673598483a">v</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He leaves his creature starving because he cannot feed it; later he accuses it of killing people. Later he is doomed to pursue it, its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">arctic hackles / bristling,</QUOTE> through the frozen north (foreshadowing Atwood's later interest in <TTHEMETOPIC>northern monsters</TTHEMETOPIC>), where at last it is happy. Finally it speaks, and it in turn accuses: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">You sliced me loose / and said it was / Creation. . . . I prowl. / I will not come when you call.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Frankenstein x" DBREF="34019" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:76627c2f-b08f-40b5-beeb-e4673598483a">x</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <SCHOLARNOTE><P>The numbers in the last four citations are those of poems, not pages.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Circle Game</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33949" PLACEHOLDER="MA, The Circle Game, 1966" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:1ce21d99-2827-4401-8f1d-99b4300c5cc4"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="JEB" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1966">1966</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> published her first major book of <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poems</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Circle Game</TITLE>, <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>whose opening sequence (from which it is titled) had appeared from <ORGNAME STANDARD