uction line on which consumers are shaped. While she has a hungry core which is not being nourished, she becomes less and less able to face food. Her final symbolic action is her baking for Peter a cake in the shape of a woman.</TTECHNIQUES></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Surfacing</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33954" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Surfacing, 1972" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:1fd1132f-5d2c-4bc4-acda-4011ed6bae27"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="JEB" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1972-09" CERTAINTY="BY">September 1972</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Surfacing</TITLE>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> which reflects her preoccupation with <TTHEMETOPIC><SOCALLED>metamorphosis</SOCALLED></TTHEMETOPIC> and with the <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><GEOG REG="Canada">Canadian</GEOG></PLACE> wilderness</TTHEMETOPIC>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="NEOS" DBREF="2742" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:a02f032c-176f-4c9f-9125-4e2c6ccc583b"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="FC" DBREF="107913" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:e5b0bfc8-0600-4e93-a0d7-bd3b45d345bb"/></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS>A French translation by <NAME STANDARD="Girod, Marie-France" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:14cce792-4f75-4c73-8e40-55bc5b1bcf94">Marie-France Girod</NAME> as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Surfacing">Faire surface, roman</TITLE> appeared in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Montreal</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Quebec"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE> in 1978. In 1987 <ORGNAME STANDARD="Treasure Press" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0301d814-1e79-4d78-9f17-b6d6e5a40e8d">Treasure Press</ORGNAME> of London, UK, issued <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Surfacing</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Lady Oracle</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Edible Woman</TITLE> together in the form of an omnibus volume.<BIBCITS/></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">The unnamed, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="pregnancy">pregnant</TMOTIF> heroine or protagonist of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Surfacing</TITLE> is almost alone in this novel, inhabiting a <PLACE><GEOG REG="Canada">Canadian</GEOG></PLACE> summer cottage in a place which is not city, nor cultivated land, nor any longer truly wilderness (as it was during her childhood summers) because of the cottages built in it by human beings in search of solitude or pretended solitude. She has travelled there to try to unravel the mystery of her father's mysterious disappearance. <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">This protagonist is fascinated by the literal underwater space beside her house, by the island in the lake to which she retreats as if for some initiation ritual, and by a metaphorical submerged state from which she struggles to emerge.</TTECHNIQUES></TSETTINGPLACE> <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL"><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">Atwood's images here of the quest and of the shaman or seer are drawn in part from Native North American culture.</TTECHNIQUES></PINFLUENCESHER></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="INFORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO"><RRECOGNITIONS>In 2004 this novel was ranked fourth in its <SOCALLED>Top 10 Reads</SOCALLED> by an unusual, prize-winning, all-male reading club meeting in a pub in a northern town in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Smith 7" DBREF="27686" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:f2c70d57-6ebe-41e9-bd13-0f977a212e87">7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRECOGNITIONS> This honour suggests that Atwood's following in Britain is not restricted either to academic circles, to women, or to her most recent work.</RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Lady Oracle</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33965" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Lady Oracle, 1976" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:39c3e9b9-45ff-465a-8eb0-c52c193e1de0"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="JEB" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="PERIOD"><DATE VALUE="1976-07-01" CERTAINTY="BY">By July 1976</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> published her <TGENRE GENRENAME="MOCKFORMS">mock-<TGENRE GENRENAME="GOTHIC">gothic</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romance</TGENRE></TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Lady Oracle</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BRI 1: 225" DBREF="1704" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:a11d152f-ac54-417a-8de8-99356a7b5f51">1: 225</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TGENREISSUE><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="PARODY" GENDEROFAUTHOR="WOMAN">In this book she <TGENRE GENRENAME="MOCKFORMS">parodies</TGENRE> the conventions of the English <TGENRE GENRENAME="GOTHIC">metaphysical gothic <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romance</TGENRE></TGENRE> on which she had been planning to write a doctoral thesis. The actual threats which are posed by contemporary society to the well-being of her female characters are very different from the apparent threats dramatised and magnified by the gothic vision.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></TGENREISSUE> Her protagonist here, <TCHARACTERNAME>Joan Foster</TCHARACTERNAME>, has trouble with shifting identities, governed in part by the shifting appearances which fashion expects of a woman.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Life Before Man</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33966" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Life Before Man, 1979" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:dfbff0e0-078d-4d59-b2a7-80d76a326918"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONST