RI 1: 225" DBREF="1704" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:a11d152f-ac54-417a-8de8-99356a7b5f51">1: 225</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>According to critic <NAME STANDARD="Grace, Sherrill" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2640412e-d9ec-4321-b41f-fe09fd69e9b8">Sherrill Grace</NAME>, the germ of this novel is to be found in a story, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">A Travel Piece</TITLE>, included in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Dancing Girls and Other Stories</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Grace viii" DBREF="33947" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:52022b48-e98a-45ed-9be2-b871cc998ef9">viii</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TCHARACTERNAME>Rennie Wilford</TCHARACTERNAME> is young and successful, with a boyfriend, a large social circle, and a crowded schedule. A brush with breast cancer and a partial mastectomy upset her life (partly by removing the boyfriend) and she takes an assignment on a Caribbean island where she intends to write up the tourist facilities. She finds it a place of frightening violence and corruption, into which she is drawn by an American dropout figure whom she comes to suspect of nefarious doings.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Amid a chorus of praise, <NAME STANDARD="Davey, Frank" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:8b312001-d855-44c6-93b6-bd2e95cdbf7a">Frank Davey</NAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Canadian Forum</TITLE> discerned a movement which he described as becoming habitual with <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Alienation from natural order . . . followed by descent into a more primitive but healing reality . . . and finally some reestablishment of order.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> With hindsight, this does not seem like an established pattern in Atwood's plots.</RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Criticism, Editing, Living as a Writer</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Survival</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33968" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Survival, 1972" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3146596c-ca6a-4913-abbc-c2b6da9089d5"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="JEB" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1972">1972</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Survival">Survival, A Thematic Guide to <TTHEMETOPIC>Canadian Literature</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>, a book of distinctively Canadian <TGENRE GENRENAME="LITERARYCRITICISM">literary and cultural criticism</TGENRE> which has proved highly influential.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS/></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> calls this work <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a diagram of Canadian literature,</QUOTE> which explores the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">common themes</QUOTE> of <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><GEOG REG="Canada">Canadian</GEOG></PLACE> aesthetic identity</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS/></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>An Unpublished Spoof</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED"><PAUTHORSHIP COLLABORATION="COLLABORATIONYES">An abortive 1970s fundraising project (apparently for the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Writers' Union of Canada" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:461063dc-7fa4-4be6-b48c-5844dadc4117">Writers' Union of Canada</ORGNAME>) had a number of writers planning to collaborate on a <TGENRE GENRENAME="EROTICAPORNOGRAPHY">pornographic</TGENRE> fiction, which would be written in hilarity and make a large profit.</PAUTHORSHIP></PMOTIVES> The collaboration came to nothing, but <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons