>Good Bones and Simple Murders</TITLE>, Toronto, 1994, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Bones and Murder</TITLE>, London, UK, 1995.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MAN">Several stories in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Good Bones</TITLE> delight in giving something to say for themselves to literary characters generally understood to be beyond sympathy (the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>stepmother</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>ugly sister</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, Gertrude in <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:cf31f8e7-ff5a-463a-adb8-20d1e1c5d8a3">Shakespeare</NAME>'s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hamlet</TITLE>).</TINTERTEXTUALITY> Others employ <TGENRE GENRENAME="FANTASY">fantasy</TGENRE>, often combined with the traditional technique of narration by a naive observer from outside the society described. In <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Homelanding</TITLE> a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>representative human being (female, Canadian)</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> explains about society on her home planet to the inhabitants of another whose life has nothing in common with ours except death. In <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Cold-blooded</TITLE> an inhabitant of a planet where the dominant species are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>insect</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>s reports in her letters home about the earth, where she is shocked by the treatment of insects but encouraged by having formed the opinion that the human race cannot last much longer. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ANSWER" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MAN">In <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">My Life as a Bat</TITLE> a former bat now re-incarnated as a human being expresses some nostalgia for her former identity and critiques <NAME STANDARD="Stoker, Bram" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:6582c605-c6a4-46fa-b8ea-d2d750fab136">Bram Stoker</NAME> for his concept of vampires.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></TVOICENARRATION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">A younger Canadian novelist, <NAME STANDARD="Van Herk, Aritha" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0006dcf5-d55f-4faa-8f80-b61b1197c64e">Aritha Van Herk</NAME>, called <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Good Bones</TITLE> and its predecessor <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Murder in the Dark</TITLE><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">aphoristic contemporary parables,</QUOTE> which <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">contain some of Atwood's most provocative and intellectually adroit writing.</QUOTE></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Bottle</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="34059" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Bottle, 2004" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:efb8296f-dd41-4802-b305-a01c850096d9"/><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMODEOFPUBLICATION PUBLICATIONMODE="LIMITEDEDITION">In 2004 the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Hay Festival Press" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:42ee9812-c34b-43e2-8803-3cca64cf8f20">Hay Festival Press</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Hay-on-Wye</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Brecknockshire"/> in <GEOG>Wales</GEOG></PLACE> printed <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME>'s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Bottle</TITLE>, a small-sized book in a limited edition of a thousand copies, a hundred of which the author signed. <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>She also drew the frontispiece, a woman looking at her reflection in (or her head inside?) a bottle, the kind of bottle from which a genie might emerge.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><BIBCITS/></PMODEOFPUBLICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>These nine <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">extremely short stories</TGENRE> (three previously in print) deal with a <TGENRE GENRENAME="MYTH">mythic past</TGENRE> which merges in the contemporary present, compressing huge stretches of time or reaching effortlessly into <TGENRE GENRENAME="FANTASY">fantasy</TGENRE>. The first, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Bottle</TITLE>, is a dialogue in which a woman strikes a bargain with a male deity, is offered immortality in a bottle, and is warned not to fall in. In the last, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Bottle II</TITLE>, a tiny, whispery voice emerges from a bottle bought as a curio. What the two bottles have common is the dust inside them. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE">Other stories retell familiar tales or legends: <TCHARACTERNAME>Philomela</TCHARACTERNAME> and <TCHARACTERNAME>Procne</TCHARACTERNAME>; <TCHARACTERNAME>King Log</TCHARACTERNAME> (who is in retirement in Switzerland, growing mushrooms on his body and writing his memoirs one word at a time, while the Stork King has eaten all the frogs and sold the pond to developers); <TCHARACTERNAME>Helen</TCHARACTERNAME>, who goes from selling Kool-Aid off her front porch to causing mayhem between the husband she has left and the lover she has left with.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE">Atwood's sense of history encompasses the future as well as the present and past. <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Take Charge</TITLE> offers five vignettes of incompetent military high command about to meet its comeuppance, which begin with wooden warships and move through tanks, interplanetary missiles, science-fiction techno-weaponry, to stone axes confronting wild dogs.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGDATE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Post-Colonial</TITLE> enumerates many things that <SOCALLED>we</SOCALLED> all have or had: Victorian public buildings, flags, native inhabitants, paintings of landscapes before and after the arrival of the men in hats, but no paintings of the native inhabitants being clubbed, robbed, or ravaged by disease. Only at the end of this five-page musing do the present identities of <SOCALLED>us</SOCALLED> and <SOCALLED>them</SOCALLED> begin to be unstable. <TTONESTYLE>The compression, the inevitability, and the suggestiveness of these stories is remarkable.</TTONESTYLE></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tent</TITLE>; <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Moral Disorder</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="38967" PLACEHOLDER="MA, The Tent, 2006" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:1e98d431-48b0-437a-8e00-29c7e2d31ed8"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="2006-01-21" CERTAINTY="BY">By 21 January 2006</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME>'s volume of <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE> entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tent</TITLE> was published in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, strikingly designed and employing her own illustrations and decorations.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS></CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Van Herk D4" DBREF="38968" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4b5cb071-a9c6-45c6-9e14-86ba92516242">D4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The black, white, and red cover of this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">small and elegant book, bijou-like in size and character,</QUOTE> represents a pyramid or tent made of words, flanked by apparent decorative tendrils which a closer look reveals to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">dog devils waving tails of flame.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Van Herk D4" DBREF="38968" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4b5cb071-a9c6-45c6-9e14-86ba92516242">D4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><TTONESTYLE>Novelist and critic <NAME STANDARD="Van Herk, Aritha" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0006dcf5-d55f-4faa-8f80-b61b