e third person about a woman named Nell; seven are first-person narratives.</TVOICENARRATION> In the opening story Nell and her partner are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>old people face to face with death</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> (as well as with the ceaseless flow of <TTHEMETOPIC>bad news from the global world</TTHEMETOPIC> beyond). After that the remaining pieces trace a woman's fairly <TTHEMETOPIC>humdrum life-experience</TTHEMETOPIC> from childhood through maturity to the <TTHEMETOPIC>deaths of her parents</TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Reviewing this book, <NAME STANDARD="Guin, Ursula K. Le">Ursula Le Guin</NAME> proposed the title <SOCALLED>story suite</SOCALLED> for a book of linked short narratives, yet expressed some doubts about the unified structure of the work under review (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">variable, elusive, even a bit slippery. This is, after all, a book by Margaret Atwood</QUOTE>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Guin 24" DBREF="43068" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3fcb9ae6-07f3-489f-b47f-ec8cb6857746">24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She was nonetheless enthusiastic, finding the opening story to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">stunning</QUOTE> in its wit, energy, and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">achingly keen sense of fear and pain.</QUOTE> Her final sentence was: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">There really is nobody like her.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Guin 24" DBREF="43068" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3fcb9ae6-07f3-489f-b47f-ec8cb6857746">24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">I'm Starved for You</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="71906" PLACEHOLDER="MA, I'm Starved for You, 2012" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9735f590-60a4-4717-8431-80e39046b50d"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="2012-03">Early March 2012</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><PMODEOFPUBLICATION><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> published her <TGENRE GENRENAME="SCIENCEFICTION">speculative-fiction</TGENRE> instalment or <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novella</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">I'm Starved for You</TITLE>, not on paper but electronically, through the digital publisher <ORGNAME STANDARD="Byliner Fiction" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0797fba3-f730-485a-9286-c0722fdc0bae">Byliner Fiction</ORGNAME>.</PMODEOFPUBLICATION> It developed into a series of which the overall title was <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Positron</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Van Herk R10" DBREF="71905" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2f8a690a-ae32-46fe-a15f-6797bad2f06c">R10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">This work features a dysfunctional society much like that of her <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">MaddAdam</TITLE> trilogy of novels: mass unemployment, starvation, street violence. The story's central characters have opted to escape all this by voluntary incarceration and surveillance in tightly ruled and fenced community called Consilience.</TSETTINGPLACE> Even within this rigid system, human desire for the forbidden arises.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Van Herk, Aritha" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0006dcf5-d55f-4faa-8f80-b61b1197c64e">Aritha Van Herk</NAME> wrote that Atwood <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sets up a completely plausible universe, as seamless as a stocking, and shockingly believable.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Van Herk R10" DBREF="71905" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2f8a690a-ae32-46fe-a15f-6797bad2f06c">R10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Stone Mattress</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="81525" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Stone Mattress, 2014" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:e0cc4eb1-21e8-4201-b3a3-0809d49f2b9b"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="2014-08">August 2014</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> returned to <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short fiction</TGENRE> with the nine stories in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Stone Mattress</TITLE>, titled from the colloquial term for a stromatolite, a rare form of fossil.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS/> <SCHOLARNOTE><P>In the USA the publisher was <ORGNAME REG="Nan A. Talese" STANDARD="Knopf Doubleday">Nan A. Talese</ORGNAME>, an imprint of Doubleday. The date is that of British publication.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>Atwood developed the title story when she was writer in residence on an <PLACE><AREA>Arctic</AREA></PLACE> cruise.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>In these stories the present is usually shadowed by vistas of the past. They are shot through, too, with <TGENRE GENRENAME="FANTASY">fantasy</TGENRE>: both fantasy conceived by the author and that conceived by the characters. The latter often serve to keep their inventors comfortable: the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="old woman">geriatric woman</TMOTIF> in the final story lives contentedly with beings whom no-one else can see. The former often twist something actual and current towards deeply uncomfortable reading: outside that old woman's cocooned existence a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">violent populist group</TMOTIF> called <SOCALLED>Our Turn</SOCALLED> rages against old people as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the parasitic dead wood at the top,</QUOTE> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the dustballs under the bed.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> Another character who hears voices (in one of three stories featuring women formerly involved with the same male poet) is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">fantasy novelist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> whose relationship with the poet was doomed by his dismissive incomprehension of her invented world. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS" SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">The most distant past is that invoked in the title story, in which the titular stone mattress, a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fossilized cushion, formed by layer upon layer of blue-green algae building up into a mound or dome,</QUOTE><BIBCITS/> has lain still for centuries in the high <PLACE><AREA>Arctic</AREA></PLACE> until it is used as a murder weapon by an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">elderly widow</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who finds that her fellow cruise passengers include a man who <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rape">raped</TMOTIF> her when they were highschool students.</TSETTINGPLACE> In response to a commission to revisit a character from an earlier work, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> wrote a story with a surprise involvement for Zenia, whose funeral featured in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Robber Bride</TITLE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION>Questioned about the number of older, female protagonists, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> denied that any homage was intended to <NAME STANDARD="Laurence, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:f60cb2c0-2cb3-4dec-888e-603388677a9e">Margaret Laurence</NAME>'s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Stone Angel</TITLE>, and maintained that about half her narrators were male, but they passed unnoticed by commentators.<BIBCITS/></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Oursonette</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="94226" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Oursonette, 2017" REF="https://commons.c