future <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG>, coinciding more or less with <REGION>New England</REGION></PLACE>.</RBESTKNOWNWORK></TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS/></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>It came out in the UK and the <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">US</GEOG></PLACE> in spring 1986.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Ustopia 26" DBREF="70827" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23f20627-a274-4888-9a84-67b533ed5490">26</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></PEDITIONS> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> suggested in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Curious Pursuits</TITLE>, 2005, <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL">that it was a trip to <PLACE><GEOG>Afghanistan</GEOG></PLACE> that first gave her the idea for this work; in 2016 she implied that was visiting the then-Communist countries of <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Germany" REG="GDR">East Germany</GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><GEOG REG="Czechoslovakia" CURRENT="Czech Republic">Czechoslovakia</GEOG></PLACE> in 1984 when she was living in West Berlin.</PINFLUENCESHER> <PATTITUDES>She has also said that she tried to fend off this horrifying story (with its technical problems of incredibility, <TGENRE GENRENAME="ALLEGORY">allegory</TGENRE>, or sermonizing) and set the manuscript aside, but she later finished it nonetheless.</PATTITUDES> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Handmaid in Age of Trump" DBREF="91966" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:1202f034-7f53-4eb3-a8c0-569c7ef1dd43"/> <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Guardian book club, Review 7" DBREF="45565" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2dd83299-8811-47bc-9646-67a16f171ffd">Review 7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She began serious work on it in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Berlin</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Germany"/></PLACE> in spring 1984. while on a fellowship which enabled her to visit <PLACE><GEOG>Poland</GEOG></PLACE> and other then Communist countries. After these experiences of totalitarian societies which aimed to be utopian, she continued writing in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE> and finished in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Tuscaloosa</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>Alabama</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"/></PLACE>.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> She set herself a rule for the story: not to include <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">anything that humankind had not already done, or for which it did not already have the tools.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Ustopia 26" DBREF="70827" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23f20627-a274-4888-9a84-67b533ed5490">26</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PNONBOOKMEDIA><NAME STANDARD="Pinter, Harold" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4d6c2cac-a5cb-42db-8c5f-af8854b60def">Harold Pinter</NAME> wrote the script for a film with the same title based on the novel, which was released in 1990, directed by <NAME STANDARD="Schlöndorff, Volker" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:5c7f391c-a3c8-4558-8b42-5179e1bb5947">Volker Schlöndorff</NAME> and starring <NAME STANDARD="Richardson, Natasha" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:c2e4d38f-1102-4483-aa1e-ec8c91de6997">Natasha Richardson</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Dunaway, Fay" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:52232dc6-293e-4904-bb19-772e6bd81d68">Fay Dunaway</NAME>, and <NAME STANDARD="Duvall, Robert" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:73939590-92dc-4294-b3de-4641a9202678">Robert Duvall</NAME>. In 2002 <NAME STANDARD="Ruders, Poul" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4d4a24f0-f822-4fdd-b2d6-96f04ab0948b">Poul Ruders</NAME>'s opera based on the novel and again sharing its title was performed at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="English National Opera" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:a4a9bd2a-fa53-450d-aeca-d2d6e316f928">English National Opera</ORGNAME> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"/><GEOG REG="England"/></PLACE>. A <ORGNAME STANDARD="Canadian National Opera" REF="https://commons.cw