no names of their own, but are named from the man to whom they belong: the heroine is <TCHARACTERNAME>Offred</TCHARACTERNAME>, or <SOCALLED>of Fred</SOCALLED>. In her dreams of resistance she is deeply encouraged by the smallest signs of other women's having shared her desire to resist. The ending is left open to interpretation or speculation: Offred is speeding away as she has longed to, but is the van that carries her headed for freedom or not? A coda set in the year 2195, during which the events of the novel are presented as having been uncovered by historical research, shows the society of the novel as having now become a topic for academic study: yet even scholarly condescension to the period studied cannot conceal the fact that many changes initiated by Gilead have not been reversed.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRECOGNITIONS><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> won her second <RRECOGNITIONNAME>Governor-General's Medal</RRECOGNITIONNAME> for this novel.<SCHOLARNOTE><P>Bibliographer <NAME STANDARD="Meier, John" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3eb1c0e9-2435-45c7-931b-d6070cde3985">John Meier</NAME>'s collection of Governor-General's-winning novels includes a copy of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Handmaid's Tale</TITLE> inscribed from Atwood (<SOCALLED>Peggy A.</SOCALLED>) to <NAME STANDARD="MacEwen, Gwendolyn" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ffb5e194-c275-4441-89a1-e5c19b870855">Gwendolyn MacEwen</NAME>, whose poetry has twice won the award.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Lederman R2" DBREF="52846" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3405ce8a-e852-471d-a114-463fdcbe7583">R2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></RRECOGNITIONS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">A review in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Library Journal</TITLE> called this book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a startling departure</QUOTE> from Atwood's previous work, and linked the ideology of Gilead to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">far-right <NAME STANDARD="Schafly, Phyllis" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:464ad803-6a44-4151-a6f9-e7728452b7db">Schafly</NAME>/<NAME STANDARD="Falwell, Jerry" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:16020b93-007f-4728-9834-d332cdb45f36">Falwell</NAME>-type ideals.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/><NAME STANDARD="McCarthy, Mary" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9b19fb17-552a-44be-9366-b3e5f736cdb5">Mary McCarthy</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times</TITLE> was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">largely negative</QUOTE>, finding the story both unlikely and unimaginative.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Ustopia 26" DBREF="70827" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23f20627-a274-4888-9a84-67b533ed5490">26</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <PCIRCULATION>But the novel made Atwood an international and interdisciplinary figure—known far beyond Canada and beyond literary circles—almost overnight. It held its place on the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times</TITLE> list of bestsellers for fifteen weeks when it first appeared, returned there for eight weeks two years later when it was reprinted in paperback, made a four-week comeback after the film of it was released in 1990 and an eighty-eight-week one after the television series in 2017 (which had two further seasons, taking the story beyond Atwood's creation). By 2017 it had been translated into forty languages and into the media of film, opera, ballet, television series and graphic novel.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Handmaid in Age of Trump" DBREF="91966" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:1202f034-7f53-4eb3-a8c0-569c7ef1dd43"/><BIBCIT DBREF="151283" PLACEHOLDER="Wheeler" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ada94f99-4e95-4e5b-882d-00378be24d02"/></BIBCITS></PCIRCULATION></P><P><RPENALTIES CENSORSHIP="CENSORSHIPYES">It has also become controversial: it is one of the respected titles discussed in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Hit List">Hit List: Freque