IOGRAPHY">autobiographical</TGENRE> content.</TGENREISSUE></CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BRI 1: 225" DBREF="1704" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:a11d152f-ac54-417a-8de8-99356a7b5f51">1: 225</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION>It is told from the point of view of the protagonist, <TCHARACTERNAME>Elaine Risley</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">middle-aged, successful painter</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> looking back at her life.</TVOICENARRATION> Elaine spent her early childhood in the northern bush with her mother, elder brother and entomologist father. <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PRESENT"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">Once living in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE> and attending school, intensely dissatisfied with the restrictions of her life, she became the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">victim or scapegoat</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> of three persecuting <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="female friendship"><SOCALLED>friends</SOCALLED></TMOTIF>, especially Cordelia. Now Elaine is back in Toronto for a retrospective exhibition of her work, and the past threatens to overwhelm her.</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGDATE> Her initial success came from her attempts to paint the experience of cruelty, the body of the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>(female) torturer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. She expects to re-encounter Cordelia (as she does re-encounter her own <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>first husband</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>), but Cordelia (last glimpsed in a mental home) remains an absence. Instead Elaine achieves resolution by visiting the ravine where the friends abandoned her in winter, so that she narrowly escaped dying of frost-bite. On that occasion she was given the will to live by a <TTHEMETOPIC>vision of the Virgin Mary</TTHEMETOPIC>. This is one of the experiences that she has tried to paint, presenting her own truth and refusing identification with any agenda, label, or commitment to a cause or movement, whether feminist or aesthetic. The disturbing story of <TTHEMETOPIC>childhood cruelty</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="secret">secrecy</TMOTIF> is left deliberately unresolved, though the link is made with adult persecutions (whether racial, political, or religious).</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Robber Bride</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="33977" PLACEHOLDER="MA, The Robber Bride, 1993" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ed8ed66d-84a3-4207-a375-7f5e72531982"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1993-10-07">7 October 1993</DATE> <CHRONPROSE>In her <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Robber Bride</TITLE>, <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> set out a <TGENRE GENRENAME="GOTHIC">gothic</TGENRE> plot about an unsisterly woman who systematically wrecks the lives of her friends.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS/></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Atwood, who says this novel <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">does not deify women,</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Guardian book club, Review 7" DBREF="45565" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2dd83299-8811-47bc-9646-67a16f171ffd">Review 7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> has also said that here she set out to restore to the range of possible characters the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE><FOREIGN LANG="fr">femme fatale</FOREIGN></TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, who had been banished from fiction first by 1950s domesticity and then by the women's movement.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The friends, Tony, Roz and Charis, attend the funeral of Zenia, who has been fascinating and seducing men and using and manipulating women <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="female friendship"