ble speed</TTHEMETOPIC>. Other visible survivors are non-human: animals, most of them laboratory-bred hybrids (like dog-shaped but ferocious wolvogs and huge truculent pigoons, pigs which contain human genetic material since they were bred for organ transplant), birds (blessedly familiar), and the race of <SOCALLED>Crakers</SOCALLED>.</TSETTINGDATE> These are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>biogenetically constructed humanoids</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> (of whom the first specimens glimpsed by the reader are a bunch of immensely attractive children) invented by the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>mad scientist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Crake</TCHARACTERNAME>. Crake was Jimmy's friend when both were growing up; his stellar scientific career ended in megalomania. Jimmy (in the pre-plague biotech world of the novel's past tense, <SOCALLED>the time before</SOCALLED>, which has changed him into the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">tattered, starving, tree-dwelling</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> Snowman) was a word-man rather than a numbers man: doomed, therefore to an inferior, penny-pinching educational establishment and a hand-to-mouth career, until Crake recruited him as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">publicist and copy-writer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> in his top-secret scientific corporation. Jimmy, though joylessly promiscuous, was fascinated by <TCHARACTERNAME>Oryx</TCHARACTERNAME>, who began her life as an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">Asian village child sold into prostitution</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> by her family in order to feed the others, and who was later employed by Crake to teach his human-like creatures.</TPLOT></P><P><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">The world <SOCALLED>before</SOCALLED> is a slightly exaggerated and unmercifully <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satirised</TGENRE> version of today's reality: gated communities, vertiginous inequalities, frequently mutating viruses, sadistic pornography online, and commodification of everything.</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE> True to Atwood's principles, she finds the originals of all her mutant life-forms, weaponry, and technological means of social control, in actuality. Jimmy, who as a student watched endless pornography and <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="WOMAN">used a computer to make nude video versions of <NAME STANDARD="Austen, Jane" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:772c02be-78f8-4c43-bf10-2be3ee77ce92">Austen</NAME>'s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Pride and Prejudice</TITLE> and <NAME STANDARD="Woolf, Virginia" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:fc1bcd5a-22ed-42e6-acaa-3ec424271faf">Woolf</NAME>'s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">To the Lighthouse</TITLE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Showalter 35" DBREF="21147" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2955cd0b-38ca-44af-bdd7-0b228c403286">35</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> is now is haunted by scraps of literature and soothes his terrors with litanies of fine-sounding but obsolete words.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> has called the book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a fun-packed, joke-filled, rollicking adventure tale about the end of the human race.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Guardian book club, Review 7" DBREF="45565" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:2dd83299-8811-47bc-9646-67a16f171ffd">Review 7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She also says it features a technocracy, an anarchy, and in its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">genetically engineered quasi-humans</QUOTE> a misguided attempt at creating utopia.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Ustopia 27" DBREF="70827" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23f20627-a274-4888-9a84-67b533ed5490">27</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Trilogy: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONO