ival" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3e0049f7-2d13-48be-aa61-a7565a55b666">International Book Festival</ORGNAME>, Atwood tweeted about the event's success.</PADVERTISING> <PEDITIONS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Year of the Flood</TITLE> was early available as an e-book as well as on paper.</PEDITIONS> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Barber R1-R2" DBREF="59509" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:440ba9fb-c0fa-4c99-a4a0-902735a4b5d3">R1-R2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It is, she insists, not a sequel to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oryx and Crake</TITLE> but a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sibling book</QUOTE> or different chapters in the same one, since the events in both novels are simultaneous (their present in the new anarchy, their past memories in the technocracy which was wiped out by sudden, mortal disease).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Ustopia 27" DBREF="70827" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23f20627-a274-4888-9a84-67b533ed5490">27</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It is now being called volume two of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">MaddAdam</TITLE> trilogy, titled from the third and final volume.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE">The present of this story is a world irrevocably changed by the cataclysmic though metaphorical flood (the onset not of water but of a quick-acting virus). Its pre-flood past (during which its characters grew up) was a dystopic world whose distorted outlines are those of our own. The story is set in a world irrevocably changed by <TTHEMETOPIC>genetic engineering</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>species crossing</TTHEMETOPIC> even before the final disaster: before that it was the same world in which, in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Oryx and Crake</TITLE>, Jimmy grew up to become <TCHARACTERNAME>Snowman</TCHARACTERNAME>, but it is now seen not from the sealed-off enclaves of middle-class life but from the dangerous, chaotic, urban pleeblands. For the few survivors, years are now dated from the cataclysm.</TSETTINGDATE></P><P>The story focuses on three women: Toby (who loses her loving, low-ranking parents to the system, survives <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">sexual violence</TMOTIF>, and becomes a not wholly believing member of a <TTHEMETOPIC>sect of ecologists or nature-worshippers</TTHEMETOPIC> calling themselves God's Gardeners), Ren (who grows up among the Gardeners, leaves them, and becomes a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>worker in this society's version of the sex trade</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>), and Amanda (an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>artist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who works in the desert forming shapes out of swarms of carrion-eating insects). All of these survive the flood when most people die. Before the flood the Gardeners were puritans who rejected the material bling that others valued, and the increasingly dubious commercially available food, to grow their own on a roof-top oasis. The <TGENRE GENRENAME="SERMON">sermons</TGENRE> of their leader, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Adam One">Adam One</TCHARACTERNAME>, punctuate the story along with their <TGENRE GENRENAME="HYMN">hymns</TGENRE> (each sermon concludes, "Let us sing") and reference to their saints (including <NAME STANDARD="Julian of Norwich" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:25cf5a77-734a-4184-9cb9-08eb68ff9f28">St Julian of Norwich</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Linnaeus, Carl" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:701db52f-324a-42b8-9ccf-d292f281fb42">St Linnaeus</NAME> of Botanical Nomenclature, <NAME STANDARD="Lovelock, James" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:f674758b-23c7-4c0d-8964-6e068545ab7b">St James Lovelock</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Stutchbury, Bridget" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:3192ba94-5d2f-49a7-a15a-aa1bdb7db2e0">St Bridget Stutchbury</NAME> of Shade Coffee, and <NAME STANDARD="Barlow, Maude" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:8bf2b608-ca97-47c4-a457-028579722d84">St Maude Barlow</NAME>).<SCHOLARNOTE><P>The last two names, of Canadian environmentalists, are rare reminders of Atwood's nationality.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></P><P>After the flood, the life which was hard becomes harder. All the central survivors variously arrive at last at the spot where Jimmy/Snowman (barely alive) is a neighbour of the Children of Crake (or <SOCALLED>Crakers</SOCALLED>, the new, genetically altered, nearly-people). All of them are still threatened by violent death from men who have survived a season of the former world's most popular sport, which was gladiatorial fighting to the death. Painballers, as they are called, are formidable opponents, being emotionally hardened and also brain-damaged; the ending of this book, therefore, is a remarkable cliff-hanger.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><NAME STANDARD="Guin, Ursula K. Le">Ursula K. Le Guin</NAME>, reviewing, noted the <TCHARACTERIZATION>rarity of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">individual characters of some complexity</QUOTE> in <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satire</TGENRE> (even Atwood's own satire), and therefore particularly welcomed the female characters here as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">real people, but heartbreaking ones.</QUOTE> Le Guin found these characters' experiences and feelings <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">vivid and memorable,</QUOTE></TCHARACTERIZATION> and the novel's ending <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a surprise, a mystery.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Guin 39" DBREF="59771" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:52a7eca6-e0b7-4316-a54b-56deb39ed044">39</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><TGENREISSUE>She also caused a furore by writing that Atwood did not want her work classified as <TGENRE GENRENAME="SCIENCEFICTION">science fiction</TGENRE> for fear of being relegated to a literary ghetto. Atwood later denied that this was true, while admitting that she prefers the term <SOCALLED>speculative fiction</SOCALLED>, as dealing with things that could happen even if they have not yet done so, more like <NAME STANDARD="Verne, Jules" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:7928f99b-0671-4069-b09f-ce5dab679576">Jules Verne</NAME> than like <NAME STANDARD="Wells, H. G." REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:a50d94c5-ba03-437a-b2b4-bb5da61a1009">H. G. Wells</NAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The War of the Worlds</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Ustopia 25-6" DBREF="70827" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:23f20627-a274-4888-9a84-67b533ed5490">25-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Trilogy: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">MaddAdam</TITLE></HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="2013-09-03">3 September 2013</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> completed her <TGENRE GENRENAME="SCIENCEFICTION">speculative-fiction</TGENRE> trilogy with a third <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">MaddAdam</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS/></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>This book opens with a story-so-far which must be hard for new readers to negotiate. Readers already steeped in this fictional world will be disappointed if they wish for a conclusion predicting its future, but not if they wish to learn more of its past, which here comes to an epic climax. The <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>human survivors</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> depicted in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Year of the Flood</TITLE> survive this violent climax, all except Jimmy (or <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Snowman">Snowman-the-Jimmy</TCHARACTERNAME>, as the Crakers now call him) and Adam (who once was <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Adam One">Adam One</TCHARACTERNAME>). Human genes are being passed on, some though not all of them mixed with Craker genes: there are babies. Human beings and Crakers (which is, of course, a human name and not what they call themselves) co-operate movingly in this story (and in crisis the Pigoons, too, surprisingly become allies), but it is clear that their continued co-existence will not be easy. Crakers have none of the heroic human individuation shared by the central characters. They eat only leaves (which means they eat all the time, as they also sing, eerily, much of the time); they find meat (<SOCALLED>a smelly bone</SOCALLED>) intolerably disgusting. They mate only in season and then a female mates with four males (the fourfathers); genetic inheritance is unknown. They believe powerfully in goodness and not at all in evil; they see Crake and Oryx as twin originating deities, powerful and beneficent. All this means that the history covered in these novels is not intelligible to them, except in simplified and santized form.</P><P><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE">The human story in this book dwells, as before, both in the present and past.</TSETTINGDATE> In the spotlight are Toby and her lover Zeb, who have lived mostly apart, and need to fill each other in about their pasts. Zeb grew up as the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>rejected, scapegoat son</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> of the man heading the Church of PetrOleum (whose church is new but whose <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>sanctimonious, sadistic hypocrisy</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> has been seen in fictional clerics before him) and as the brother of Adam, the future <TCHARACTERNAME>Adam One</TCHARACTERNAME>. Here <TTHEMETOPIC>genetic inheritance</TTHEMETOPIC> has immense importance but is for a long time unknowable. Zeb has worked undercover in a sequence of false identities, <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="DICTION">and deals with emotional pain by coarseness of language. Toby takes over from Jimmy the task of telling stories to the Crakers which translate the action into terms they can understand: simplified, sanitized, nursery-storied.</TTECHNIQUES> When a little-boy Craker named <TCHARACTERNAME>Blackbeard</TCHARACTERNAME> (according to the jokey inappropriateness once favoured by Crake) attaches himself to her she teaches him the mysteries of <TTHEMETOPIC>writing</TTHEMETOPIC>, a magic means of making paper talk. The apocalyptic showdown between the dehumanized Painballers and the tiny human fighting force (with Blackbeard and three pigoons) takes place at the former Paradice Project where Crake developed the first Crakers. For little Blackbeard this is a sacred place; he is devastated, perhaps marked forever, to discover the decayed corpses of the immortal Oryx and Crake, now <SOCALLED>a smelly bone</SOCALLED>. In the end Blackbeard inherits Toby's story-telling role. The Crakers have entered history and culture: perhaps most tellingly of all, when Toby, like Zeb before her, leaves the colony never to return, Blackbeard records the several competing explanations of where she has gone: the pigoons' version that she died alone and was eaten by vultures, as well as the Crakers' better, because happier, version: that she took spirit form and was reunited with Zeb.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME STANDARD="Greer, Andrew Sean" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:8e2c2d30-afc0-45dd-a346-2a60665a96ce">Andrew Sean Greer</NAME>'s review called the Children of Crake sexy, innocent, and exhausting. He commented on the beauty of Atwood's prose, and summarized the book as a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fitting and joyous conclusion that's an epic not only of an imagined future but of our own past, an exposition of how oral storytelling traditions led to written ones and ultimately to our sense of origin.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Heart Goes Last</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="85285" PLACEHOLDER="MA, The Heart Goes Last, 2015" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9dff5263-7cbd-432b-ae47-6e83fb88f9d1"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="PERIOD" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="2015-09">By late September 2015</DATE> <CHRONPROSE>After her <TGENRE GENRENAME="SCIENCEFICTION">speculative-fiction</TGENRE> trilogy <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> published another <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> in the same <TGENRE GENRENAME="DYSTOPIA">dystopian</TGENRE> genre but unconnected to the trilogy: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Heart Goes Last</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS/></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">This book famously began in the form of a serial entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="The Heart Goes Last">Positron</TITLE>, published online with <ORGNAME STANDARD="Byliner Fiction" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:0797fba3-f730-485a-9286-c0722fdc0bae">Byliner</ORGNAME>.</PSERIALIZATION> <PDEDICATION>As a volume it is dedicated to <NAME STANDARD="Engel, Marian" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:e61cf9a9-059e-4660-bedb-cd9a9c262929">Marian Engel</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Carter, Angela" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:4efd40b1-931f-4e12-805d-2417a71dfddc">Angela Carter</NAME>, and <NAME STANDARD="Merril, Judy" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:c43bfa5f-1955-48dc-9d75-7f168523f3ff">Judy Merril</NAME>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[a]nd for <NAME STANDARD="Gibson, Graeme" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:e4a0c2dc-af59-4db9-b3bc-e01e0db950fd">Graeme</NAME>, as ever.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Heart prelims" DBREF="85285" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9dff5263-7cbd-432b-ae47-6e83fb88f9d1">prelims</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PDEDICATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE">No cataclysm separates the time of this novel, as it does the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">MaddAdam</TITLE> books, from the present day, but only an indeterminate, shortish lapse of years.</TSETTINGDATE> Economic systems have collapsed, <TTHEMETOPIC>unemployment</TTHEMETOPIC> has reached forty percent, the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="violence">masses are desperate and violent</TMOTIF>, and the erstwhile middle classes are deprived. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS" SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">The twin town Positron/Consilience, a hyper-gated community, is run by a company which, taking note that privately-owned jails still return a profit, recruits desperate people to move there.</TSETTINGPLACE> Among the residents each couple shares its little dream home, month by month, with Alternates who are in prison while they are out.</P><P>Charmaine, who with her husband, Stan, has been scraping along <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="financial ruin">subsisting on discarded scraps and sleeping in their car</TMOTIF>, opts for Consilience and Stan opts with her. But the promise of stability proves hollow, both on the social, communal level and on the personal level. Charmaine's prison job, Special Procedures, charges her with administering the final, <TTHEMETOPIC>lethal injection to criminals</TTHEMETOPIC> beyond redemption. She prides herself on sending each one on his way blissful and contented: the book's title comes from her observation of the injection's effect. Stan, who works with poultry, has no idea what her duties are. Meanwhile the tightly prescribed status quo of Positron/Consilience is a nexus of hidden forces for violent change: on the one hand those in charge are moving into more lucrative businesses like the <TTHEMETOPIC>sale of human organs</TTHEMETOPIC>; arrayed against them are those who seek to end the social experiment altogether. The prim and cautious Charmaine is lured into a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="adultery">torrid affair</TMOTIF> with the man of her Alternate couple. The reader learns only much later that his wife, Jocelyn, who seems simply jealous and sadistic, is working to overthrow the system.</P><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY GENDEROFAUTHOR="MAN" INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONUNACKNOWLEDGED">Jocelyn has in a distant past studied English literature and is occasionally disconcerting. <TINTERTEXTUALITY GENDEROFAUTHOR="MAN" INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION"><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Do you believe in free will?</QUOTE>, she asks, out of the blue. Stan replies, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">How do you mean?</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Heart 119" DBREF="85285" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9dff5263-7cbd-432b-ae47-6e83fb88f9d1">119</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He replies <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">What?</QUOTE> when with equal abruptness she says of Charmaine: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Sufficient to have stood but free to fall.</QUOTE><NAME STANDARD="Milton, John" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d4c47846-135c-46d7-9c0b-d79cc118dd52"/> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Heart 129" DBREF="85285" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9dff5263-7cbd-432b-ae47-6e83fb88f9d1">129</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The literary allusion is unemphasized, unexplicated, un-noticeable. As the plot picks up speed and complication, Charmaine, following orders, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">administers what she believes to be the lethal dose</TMOTIF> to Stan. <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS" SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">As thrills, horrors, and farce escalate further, when they have <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="marriage ending">escaped and married and started a family, and are living their dream</TMOTIF> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Las Vegas</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Nevada"/><GEOG REG="USA"/></PLACE>,</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE> Charmaine believes she has undergone a surgical operation on her brain to fixate her love and desire forever on Stan. Jocelyn enlightens her: there was no surgery; her love is free. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The world is all before you, where to choose.</QUOTE></TINTERTEXTUALITY><NAME STANDARD="Milton, John" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:d4c47846-135c-46d7-9c0b-d79cc118dd52"/> The last words of the book are an echo: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">How do you mean? says Charmaine.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Heart 306" DBREF="85285" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:9dff5263-7cbd-432b-ae47-6e83fb88f9d1">306</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO" RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL">Several reviewers noted Atwood's ability to tread familiar territory without repeating herself, to deliver repeated plot surprises, and <TTONESTYLE>to render the most horrifying and repellant material engaging and even comedic.</TTONESTYLE><NAME STANDARD="Johnson, Mat" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:14fac26c-8b5a-4d08-b491-7fd2d1be55be">Mat Johnson</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times</TITLE> called her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a living legend who continues to remain fresh and innovative on the page.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/><NAME STANDARD="Fowles, Stacey May" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:41458725-c32b-4875-b488-6d364840e264">Stacey May Fowles</NAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Globe and Mail</TITLE> wrote that her created universe is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">not only believable, but deeply witty and oddly beautiful</QUOTE> in its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">painstakingly intricate detail.</QUOTE><BIBCITS/></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Rewriting Homer, Shakespeare</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Penelopiad</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="37366" PLACEHOLDER="MA, The Penelopiad, 2005" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:22aa2bd9-0450-4703-a453-16ea1665c955"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="2005-10-26">26 October 2005</DATE> <CHRONPROSE><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MAN"><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME> published one of the two opening titles in <ORGNAME STANDARD="Canongate" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:321bc778-b535-4bdd-acec-5cc2c78ef2dd">Canongate</ORGNAME>'s <TITLE T