E>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Water does not resist. Water flows. . . . But water always goes where it wants to go, and nothing in the end can stand against it. . . . If you can't go through an obstacle, go around it. Water does.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Penelopiad paperback 43" DBREF="42872" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:90400a1f-bab9-4fc2-bce0-5a1e63a8692f">43</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TVOICENARRATION>The prose is interrupted from time to time by the chorus of the hanged maids, who make <TGENRE GENRENAME="POPULAR">popular</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="SATIRE">satirical</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="SONG">song</TGENRE>s out of their plight.</TVOICENARRATION> Their first song is a rope-jumping or skipping rhyme: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">we are the maids / the ones you killed / the ones you failed.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Penelopiad paperback 5" DBREF="42872" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:90400a1f-bab9-4fc2-bce0-5a1e63a8692f">5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The closing line of its second stanza—<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">it was not fair</QUOTE>—recurs in their final song, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Envoi</TITLE>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">we had no voice / we had no name . . . . we took the blame / it was not fair.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood, Penelopiad paperback 195" DBREF="42872" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:90400a1f-bab9-4fc2-bce0-5a1e63a8692f">195</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>The day before International Women's Day 2007, the Canadian <ORGNAME STANDARD="National Arts Centre" REG="Centre Nationale des Arts" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:87933308-9329-4a48-9514-cd42fdd0a06f">National Arts Centre / Centre Nationale des Arts</ORGNAME> announced that donations from seven individual Canadian women were funding a production of <NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME>'s <TGENRE GENRENAME="ADAPTATION"><TGENRE GENRENAME="DRAMA">stage</TGENRE> adaptation</TGENRE> of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Penelopiad</TITLE>.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PPERFORMANCE>The NAC's co-production with the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Royal Shakespeare Company" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:97df1bb1-fd17-4df3-8a85-eee2522de944">Royal Shakespeare Company</ORGNAME> was to be seen that year, first in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG> (at <SETTLEMENT REG="Stratford upon Avon">Stratford</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Warwickshire"/></PLACE>, then in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Newcastle upon Tyne">Newcastle</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Northumberland"/><GEOG REG="England"/></PLACE>) and then in <PLACE><GEOG>North America</GEOG></PLACE>.</PPERFORMANCE><BIBCITS/> The play is now firmly fixed in the international repertoire.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Atwood's stage version, while highly theatrical, is also verbally very close to the original. The maids function as a traditional Greek chorus while they flow across the stage, now slow and now fast, working or playing or running in terror. Penelope relies on their loyalty as they spy on the suitors for her; some of the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rape">rapes</TMOTIF> taking place barely off stage are clearly even worse than others. The <TGENRE GENRENAME="FEMINIST">feminist</TGENRE> message is lucid and complex. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="female friendship">Women here are allies</TMOTIF> because only a woman can see another woman as a person instead of a <TTHEMETOPIC>sex-object</TTHEMETOPIC>; having no power, they are necessarily <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>manipulators and are prone to betray; they are natural scapegoats</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hag-Seed</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="89569" PLACEHOLDER="MA, Hag-Seed, 2016" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:441c65cf-b30b-4a1b-82b2-92e7dc3d8e17"/><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" REL