c.ca/orlando:2be47e51-584b-4b01-915d-54f3e224c22e">Future Library</ORGNAME>. Atwood is the first of what will in the end be a hundred writers, one each year, commissioned for a book in any genre. The manuscripts are to be preserved in the public library in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Oslo</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Norway"/></PLACE> for the century, after which it is planned that a hundred trees will be cut down to make the paper to print them and the future world will read them. Obviously many of the authors to be commissioned for this project are yet unborn. <PATTITUDES><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">Atwood says that for her the attractions of the idea are the message-in-a-bottle sense of writing for an unknown readership, and the bypassing of today's commentators.</PMOTIVES></PATTITUDES><BIBCITS/></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Return to Gilead: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Testaments</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>In late November, with perceived parallels to current events keeping <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Handmaid's Tale</TITLE> riding high, Atwood announced that in September 2019 she would release a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SEQUEL">sequel</TGENRE>: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Testaments</TITLE>, <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE" SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE"><TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="FUTURE">set in Gilead fifteen years after Offred's opaque exit from the scene.</TSETTINGDATE></TSETTINGPLACE> The book is to be launched in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION REG="Middlesex"/> <GEOG REG="England">UK</GEOG></PLACE>, on 9 September, and the launch will be followed by a live interview at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="National Theatre" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:8bf5f057-f6f1-4dc3-88db-1dc0769ae2bd">National Theatre</ORGNAME>, to be broadcast around the world.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT DBREF="152004" PLACEHOLDER="Mark Brown" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:c4a8a46b-dff9-493b-8225-8981fc3dc0f1"/><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cain" DBREF="151282" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:5c129ca3-ff73-4427-aeae-f6526af0fa2d"/></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION>The story will be presented by the academic narrator of the previous novel, as the fruits of recent research,</TVOICENARRATION> and will feature three leading female characters.<BIBCITS/></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Papers, Interviews, Recordings</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PARCHIVALLOCATION><NAME STANDARD="Atwood, Margaret" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:b01b26bc-1d1f-47bf-84c9-c529c68de6f0">MA</NAME>'s papers held by the <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Toronto" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ab1b87c1-10a5-404f-bb05-01e3d5af9ee9">University of Toronto</ORGNAME>'s rare book collection include manuscripts of published and unpublished work.</PARCHIVALLOCATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Margaret Atwood: Conversations</TITLE>, 1990, collects interviews with Atwood at different stages of her career. <RRECOGNITIONS><PNONBOOKMEDIA>She has recorded four of her poems for <RRECOGNITIONNAME><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Poetry Archive</TITLE></RRECOGNITIONNAME>.</PNONBOOKMEDIA> <PATTITUDES>They are headed with a quotation: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TGENREISSUE>With a <TGENRE GENRENAME="LYRIC">lyric</TGENRE> poem you look, and meditate, and put the rock back. With <TGENRE GENRENAME="FICTION">fiction</TGENRE> you poke things with a stick to see what will happen.</TGENREISSUE></QUOTE></PATTITUDES><BIBCITS/></RRECOGNITIONS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Recent tributes include one from <NAME STANDARD="Lucas, Caroline" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orlando:ef0ed60a-6c7e-42b7-ac04-a209637cf2f6">Caroline Lucas</NAME>, Britain's first member of parliament representing the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Green Party" REF="https://commons.cwrc.ca/orland